window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2007>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2007","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"You have been provided a retort stand, clamp and boss, a pendulum bob, a piece of thread and other necessary apparatus. carry out the following experiment.    (i) Setup the apparatus as shown in the diagram above  (ii) Measure and record the distance  l  = 130 cm from the centre of the bulb to the point of suspension of the pendulum.  (iii) Displace the pendulum through a small angle and release. Allow the pendulum to oscillate freely  (iv) Determine the time t for 20 oscillations  (v) Also determine the period T of the oscillations  (vi) Evaluate T2 and L =  l  - 30  (vii) Repeat the procedure for four other values of  l  = 110, 90, 70 and 50 cm.  (viii) In each case determine t and evaluate T, T2  and L. Tabulate your reading  (ix) Plot the graph T2  on the vertical axis against L on the horizontal axis starting both axes  from origin (0,0)  (x) Determine the slope, s, of the graph, also determine the intercept, C on the T2 axis  (xi) Evaluate: I. k1 = 4\u03c02s\\frac{4\u03c0^{2}}{s}s4\u03c02\u200b II. k2 = cs\\frac{c}{s}sc\u200b   (take \u03c0 = 227\\frac{22}{7}722\u200b)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/N l (cm)t1(s)t2(s)t = t1+t22\\frac{t_{1}+t_{2}}{2}2t1\u200b+t2\u200b\u200b(s)T = tn\\frac{t}{n}nt\u200b(s)T2(s2)L =  l  - 30 (cm)1130.0045.7045.5045.602.285.198100.002110.0041.3041.5041.402.074.28580.00390.0038.7039.0038.851.943.66460.00470.0034.1034.1034.101.712.92440.00550.0029.0029.3029.151.462.23220.00        (x) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 4.625\u22122.25100\u221220\\frac{4.625-2.25}{100-20}100\u2212204.625\u22122.25\u200b = 2.3750.8\\frac{2.375}{0.8}0.82.375\u200b = 0.030  C = 1.473    (xi) I. k1 = 4\u03c02s\\frac{4\u03c0^{2}}{s}s4\u03c02\u200b = 4\u00d7(227)20.03\\frac{4\u00d7\\left(\\frac{22}{7}\\right)^{2}}{0.03}0.034\u00d7(722\u200b)2\u200b = 1317.00 II. k2 = Cs\\frac{C}{s}sC\u200b = 1.4730.03\\frac{1.473}{0.03}0.031.473\u200b = 49.1    (xii)  Precautions:   1. I ensured that the amplitude of oscillation was kept very small to maintain simple harmonic motion, as large amplitudes could introduce non-linear motion and affect accuracy.  2. I checked that the support of the cord was firm and stable to prevent any unwanted movement or vibrations, which could alter the oscillation and lead to inconsistent results.  3. I verified that the cord was securely attached and free from any slack, ensuring smooth and uniform oscillations.  4. I minimized external disturbances by conducting the experiment in a draft-free area, reducing the risk of interference with the oscillation.  5. I repeated the measurements multiple times to account for any minor variations and improve the accuracy of the results.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2007>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2007","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"What is meant by the period of oscillations of an oscillating body?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The period of oscillations of an oscillating body is the time taken for the body to complete one full cycle of motion, returning to its starting position. It represents the duration of one complete oscillation and is measured in seconds.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2007>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2007","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"GRAVITATIONAL FIELD : ACCELERATION DUE TO GRAVITY","question":"Explain the acceleration of free fall due to gravity.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The acceleration of free fall due to gravity is the rate at which an object accelerates towards the Earth when it is in free fall, unaffected by air resistance. This acceleration is approximately 9.81\u2009m/s2 near the Earth's surface and is denoted by the symbol g. It means that for each second an object falls, its velocity increases by about 9.81\u2009m/s, causing it to accelerate downward until it reaches terminal velocity or impacts the ground. This acceleration is a result of the gravitational force exerted by the Earth on the object.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2007>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2007","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Using the above diagram as a guide carry out the following experiment    (i) Place the equilateral triangular glass prism on the drawing paper. Trace the outline ABC of the prism  (ii) Remove the prism. Draw a line NO such that it make an angle i = 25\u00b0 with the normal at point O on side AB.  (iii) Fix two pins R1 and R2 vertically on line NO. replace the prism on its outline  (iv) Place the reflecting surface of the mirror in contact with face AC of the prism  (v) Looking through face bc of the prism fix two other pins at R3 and R4 such that the pins appear to be in a straight line with the images of the pins at R1 and R2  (vi) Remove the prism, the mirror and the pins, Draw a line to join points R3 and R4  (vii) Produce R4R3 to meet the line NO at T  (viii) Measure and record the angles \u03b8 at T and e at D  (ix) Repeat the procedure for four other values of i = 30\u00b0, 35\u00b0, 40\u00b0,  and 45\u00b0. In each case, measure and record the corresponding values of \u03b8 and e. Tabulate your reading  (x) Plot a graph e on the vertical axis and \u03b8 on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from origin (0,0)  (xi) Determine the slope, s, of the graph and intercept on the horizontal axis.  (xii) Evaluate k = s-1  (xiii) State two precaution taken to ensure accurate results  [ Attach your traces to your answer booklet ].","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/Ni\u00b0e\u00b0\u03b8\u00b012522.8970.0023029.0060.4033535.1137.9544037.1039.9654545.2021.70        (xi) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 44\u22122422.5\u221267.5\\frac{44-24}{22.5-67.5}22.5\u221267.544\u221224\u200b = 20\u221245\\frac{20}{-45}\u22124520\u200b = -0.444  Intercept on the horizontal axis = 125\u00b0    (xii) k = s-1 = -0.444-1 = -2.25    (xiii)  Precautions:   1. I ensured that both the object and image pins were perfectly erect to eliminate parallax error, as even slight tilting could lead to inaccurate readings.  2. I securely fastened the pins in place to maintain their upright position during the measurement process, preventing any movement that could compromise alignment.  3. I regularly checked the stability of the pins before taking readings to confirm they remained securely positioned and erect, further enhancing measurement accuracy.  4. I positioned my eye at the same level as the pins when taking measurements to minimize any viewing angle discrepancies that could lead to parallax errors.  5. I documented multiple readings and calculated an average to reduce the impact of any minor misalignments or human error, ensuring more reliable results.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2007>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2007","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : PLANE MIRROR","question":"State four characteristics of the image of an object formed by a plane mirror.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The characteristics of an image formed by a plane mirror include:    1. Virtual Image: The image is virtual, meaning it cannot be projected onto a screen as it appears to be behind the mirror.  2. Upright Orientation: The image is upright, maintaining the same orientation as the object.  3. Same Size: The image is of the same size as the object, with no magnification or reduction.  4. Laterally Inverted: The image is laterally inverted, meaning the left and right sides are swapped; for example, if the object is facing left, the image will appear to face right.  5. Equal Distance: The image is formed at an equal distance behind the mirror as the object is in front of it, maintaining the principle of reflection.  6. Distance from the Mirror: If the object moves closer to the mirror, the image moves closer as well, maintaining the same distance relationship.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2007>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2007","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State two conditions necessary for total internal reflection to occur in a medium.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Two conditions necessary for total internal reflection to occur in a medium are:    1. Light Must Be Traveling from a Denser to a Less Dense Medium: Total internal reflection occurs only when light travels from a medium with a higher refractive index (denser) to a medium with a lower refractive index (less dense).    2. Angle of Incidence Must Exceed the Critical Angle: The angle of incidence at the boundary between the two media must be greater than the critical angle for the specific pair of media. If this condition is met, total internal reflection will occur, and the light will be completely reflected back into the denser medium.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2007>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2007","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You have been provided an accumulator E, a standard resistor Rx, two resistance boxes RB1 and RB2, two keys K1 and K2 and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Measure and record the e.m.f of the accumulator  (ii) Connect the circuit as shown above  (iii) Set the resistance R, in the resistance boxes such that  R  in RB1 = R in RB2 = 1 \u03a9  (iv) With K1 open and K2 closed, measure and record the potential difference V\u03b8 across the standard resistor Rx  (v) Close K1 and K2. Read and record the potential difference V1 across Rx  (vi) Evaluate V1\u22121V^{-1}_{1}V1\u22121\u200b  (vii) Repeat procedure (v) for four other values of R = 2, 3, 4 and 5 \u03a9 respectively. In each case ensure that the value of R in RB1 is equal to the value of R in RB2  (viii) Evaluate V1\u22121V^{-1}_{1}V1\u22121\u200b in each case. Tabulate your readings  (ix) Plot a graph of V1\u22121V^{-1}_{1}V1\u22121\u200b on the vertical axis against R on the horizontal axis starting both axes at the origin (0,0)  (x) Determine the slope, s, of the graph and intercept l on the vertical axis  (xi) Evaluate y = Is\\frac{I}{s}sI\u200b  (xii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/NR(\u03a9)V1(V)V1\u22121V^{-1}_{1}V1\u22121\u200b(V-1)11.002.100.47622.001.820.54733.001.620.61744.001.440.69455.001.320.758        (x) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 5\u221210.758\u22120.476\\frac{5-1}{0.758-0.476}0.758\u22120.4765\u22121\u200b = 40.282\\frac{4}{0.282}0.2824\u200b = 14.18  l = 0.4    (xi) y = Is\\frac{I}{s}sI\u200b = 0.414.18\\frac{0.4}{14.18}14.180.4\u200b = 0.0282    (xii)  Precautions:   1. I ensured that all wires were tightly connected to prevent any loose connections, which could lead to current fluctuations and affect the accuracy of the measurements.  2. I made it a point to keep the circuit key open whenever the circuit was not in use, effectively conserving the battery life and preventing unnecessary drainage of the cells.  3. I routinely inspected all connections for signs of wear or damage to ensure optimal performance and reliability during the experiment.  4. I maintained organized wiring to avoid tangles and accidental disconnections, which could disrupt the circuit and compromise the experiment's integrity.  5. I verified the calibration of all measuring instruments before starting the experiment to ensure precise readings and reduce the potential for error.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2007>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2007","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE AND ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"Explain what is meant by  potential difference  between two points in an electric circuit.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The potential difference between two points in an electric circuit refers to the amount of work done per unit charge to move a charge from one point to the other. It indicates the energy difference that drives the flow of electric current through the circuit, effectively representing how much energy is available to do work on the charges as they move between the two points. The potential difference is measured in volts (V), with one volt defined as one joule of energy per coulomb of charge.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2007>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2007","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"A cell has an e.m.f of 3V. When it is connected across a resistor of resistance 4 \u03a9, a current of 0.5 A passes through the circuit. Calculate the internal resistance of the cell.    (Provide your answer without the unit)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"E = I(R + r)    3 = 0.5(4 + r)    3 = 2 + 0.5r    1 = 0.5r    r = 10.5\\frac{1}{0.5}0.51\u200b = 2 \u03a9","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];